"Lenton T.M., Williamson M.S., Edwards N.R., Marsh R., Price A.R., Ridgwell A.J., Shepherd J.G., Cox S.J.","Millennial timescale carbon cycle and climate change in an efficient Earth system model",2006,"Climate Dynamics","26","7-8",,"687","711",,,10.1007/s00382-006-0109-9,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33645980646&partnerID=40&md5=ec875390e351cf6b96f601eedfbd9aeb","Tyndall Centre, United Kingdom; School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich, United Kingdom; Department of Earth Sciences, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom; National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, United Kingdom; Southampton e-Science Centre, University of Southampton, Southampton, United Kingdom; Department of Earth and Ocean Sciences, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada","Lenton, T.M., Tyndall Centre, United Kingdom, School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich, United Kingdom; Williamson, M.S., Tyndall Centre, United Kingdom, School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich, United Kingdom, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, United Kingdom; Edwards, N.R., Department of Earth Sciences, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom; Marsh, R., Tyndall Centre, United Kingdom, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, United Kingdom; Price, A.R., Southampton e-Science Centre, University of Southampton, Southampton, United Kingdom; Ridgwell, A.J., Department of Earth and Ocean Sciences, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada; Shepherd, J.G., Tyndall Centre, United Kingdom, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, United Kingdom; Cox, S.J., Southampton e-Science Centre, University of Southampton, Southampton, United Kingdom","A new Earth system model, GENIE-1, is presented which comprises a 3-D frictional geostrophic ocean, phosphate-restoring marine biogeochemistry, dynamic and thermodynamic sea-ice, land surface physics and carbon cycling, and a seasonal 2-D energy-moisture balance atmosphere. Three sets of model climate parameters are used to explore the robustness of the results and for traceability to earlier work. The model versions have climate sensitivity of 2.8-3.3°C and predict atmospheric CO2 close to present observations. Six idealized total fossil fuel CO2 emissions scenarios are used to explore a range of 1,100-15,000 GtC total emissions and the effect of rate of emissions. Atmospheric CO2 approaches equilibrium in year 3000 at 420-5,660 ppmv, giving 1.5-12.5°C global warming. The ocean is a robust carbon sink of up to 6.5 GtC year-1. Under ""business as usual"", the land becomes a carbon source around year 2100 which peaks at up to 2.5 GtC year-1. Soil carbon is lost globally, boreal vegetation generally increases, whilst under extreme forcing, dieback of some tropical and sub-tropical vegetation occurs. Average ocean surface pH drops by up to 1.15 units. A Greenland ice sheet melt threshold of 2.6°C local warming is only briefly exceeded if total emissions are limited to 1,100 GtC, whilst 15,000 GtC emissions cause complete Greenland melt by year 3000, contributing 7 m to sea level rise. Total sea-level rise, including thermal expansion, is 0.4-10 m in year 3000 and ongoing. The Atlantic meridional overturning circulation shuts down in two out of three model versions, but only under extreme emissions including exotic fossil fuel resources. © Springer-Verlag 2006.",,"carbon cycle; climate change; modeling",,,,,,"Adams, B., White, A., Lenton, T.M., An analysis of some diverse approaches to modelling net primary productivity (2004) Ecol Modell, 177, pp. 353-391; Annan, J.D., Hargreaves, J.C., Edwards, N.R., Marsh, R., Parameter estimation in an intermediate complexity earth system model using an ensemble Kalman filter (2005) Ocean Modell, 8, pp. 135-1544; Archer, D., Kheshgi, H., Maier-Reimer, E., Dynamics of fossil fuel CO2 neutralization by marine CaCO3 (1998) Global Biogeochem Cycles, 12, pp. 259-276; Ba